============================================================
GEOMETRIC CLOCK INTERPRETATION OF THE ACTIVATION VARIABLE
============================================================

1. Redshift and scale factor

In a homogeneous FRW universe the redshift and scale factor satisfy

    1 + z = 1/a

where a = 1 at the present epoch.

Taking logarithms gives

    ln(1+z) = - ln a.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. Relation to the Hubble rate
------------------------------------------------------------

By definition,

    H = a_dot / a.

Therefore

    d ln a = da/a = H dt.

Using

    ln(1+z) = - ln a

we obtain

    d ln(1+z) = - d ln a = - H dt.

Thus the logarithmic redshift increment is exactly the Hubble clock
increment, up to sign.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Integrated expansion history
------------------------------------------------------------

Define the cumulative activation variable

    U(z) = ∫_0^z dz' / (1+z').

Using

    dz/(1+z) = d ln(1+z) = - H dt

this becomes

    U(z) = ∫_0^z d ln(1+z')
         = - ∫_{t0}^{t(z)} H(t') dt'.

Reversing the integration limits gives

    U(z) = ∫_{t(z)}^{t0} H(t') dt'.

Hence the activation variable is exactly the accumulated Hubble
expansion between cosmic time t(z) and the present epoch t0.


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Closed form
------------------------------------------------------------

Evaluating the integral in redshift form gives

    U(z) = ln(1+z).

Equivalently,

    U(z) = ∫_{t(z)}^{t0} H(t') dt'.

Thus the two expressions are identical:

    U(z) = ln(1+z)
         = ∫_{t(z)}^{t0} H(t') dt'.


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Physical interpretation
------------------------------------------------------------

The activation variable is therefore not an arbitrary fitting
coordinate. It is the integrated cosmological clock of the FRW
background.

It measures the total logarithmic expansion experienced between
redshift z and the present.

In this sense the activation law depends on cumulative spacetime
history rather than on instantaneous local quantities.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. Activation law in clock form
------------------------------------------------------------

The stretched-exponential activation law may therefore be written as

    g(z) = 1 − exp[ − ( U(z) / u_s )^ν ]

with

    U(z) = ∫_{t(z)}^{t0} H(t') dt'.

Equivalently,

    g(z) = 1 − exp[ − ( ln(1+z) / u_s )^ν ].

Thus the fitted activation function is exactly a cumulative response
to the integrated Hubble clock.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. Equality-tied form
------------------------------------------------------------

If

    u_s = α u_eq

with

    u_eq = (1/3) ln( (1−Ω_m)/Ω_m ),

then

    g(z) =
      1 − exp[ − ( U(z)/(α u_eq) )^ν ]

where

    U(z) = ∫_{t(z)}^{t0} H(t') dt'
         = ln(1+z).

This shows that the equality-tied model is a clock-normalised
cumulative activation law.


------------------------------------------------------------
8. Conclusion
------------------------------------------------------------

The activation variable satisfies the exact geometric identity

    U(z) = ln(1+z) = ∫_{t(z)}^{t0} H(t') dt'.

Therefore the cosmological activation law is most naturally
interpreted as a stretched-exponential response to accumulated
FRW expansion history.

The cosmological sector is thus governed by a geometric memory clock,
while the galaxy sector is governed by the local transport dynamics of
the curvature–memory field.
